      <description>&lt;p&gt;I obtained my PhD in Statistics in 2015 in a cotutelle between the &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.unige.ch/gsem/en/research/institutes/rcs&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;University of Geneva&lt;/a&gt; and the &lt;a href=&#34;https://sydney.edu.au/&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;University of Sydney&lt;/a&gt;. I then worked as a post-doctoral fellow at &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.dal.ca/faculty/science/math-stats.html&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;Dalhousie University&lt;/a&gt; as part of a Canadian Statistical Sciences Institute collaborative research team. Since 2018, I am an Assistant Professor of Statistics in the &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.stevens.edu/schaefer-school-engineering-science/departments/mathematical-sciences&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;Department of Mathematical Sciences&lt;/a&gt; at Stevens Institute of Technology.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;My research interests lie in robust statistics, semi-parametric methods, computational statistics, and spatio-temporal modeling with ecological applications. My current methodological research includes robust smoothing parameter selection for non-parametric additive models and automatic outlier detection for general state space models. Ongoing cross-disciplinary collaborations include growth estimation methods from mark-recapture data and large-scale spatio-temporal modeling of the impact of volcanic eruptions on vegetation density from satellite imagery.&lt;/p&gt;
</description>
